d review system</a> to submit.</blockquote>\r\nPlease include the email address of the main contact for the workshop, and any other contact details that will help us get in touch with you. Notification of acceptance notification will be by <b>May 8, 2011</b>.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Artifacts:</b>\r\n\r\nProposals Submission Deadline April 17, 2011<b></b>\r\n\r\nThe artifacts category seeks to provide participants with an opportunity to present work in a forum that facilitates open discussion and enables direct interaction with conference attendees. A dedicated session will be held during the conference to present the artifacts.\r\n\r\nArtifacts can be anything from design sketchbooks, to reformed organizational processes, to ads you’ve produced, to products you’ve made, to short films, to conceptual objects, etc. We encourage submissions that are thought provoking and visually engaging, and which cover exploratory/speculative work, smaller projects, unusual representations of ethnographic work, and so on. The form of the presented materials is open. In keeping with the category title artifacts though, we encourage submissions based on some material instantiation that can be exhibited at the conference. Our hope is that it will be the ‘thinginess’ of the artifacts that will, in part, prompt interaction with and between conference attendees.\r\n\r\nSubmissions should include a single page describing or illustrating the proposed submission (the one page inclusive of any and all figures and references, where appropriate). This page should convey to reviewers what the artifact being submitted is and how it is hoped to provoke discussion. The page will also be included in the published conference proceedings.\r\n\r\nAlso included in the submissions should be a paragraph and image (no more that 150 words) that can be displayed on the conference website.\r\n<blockquote>The deadline for artifact proposal submissions is April 17, 2011.\r\n\r\nIn order to submit a proposal first <a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic/preGetID\">create an account</a> then log in to the <a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic\">EPIC submission and review system</a> to submit.</blockquote>\r\nNotification of acceptance will happen by <b>May 22, 2011</b>. Accepted submissions will have their 150 word descriptions posted on the EPIC2011 website.\r\n\r\nDescriptions (including images) of accepted artifacts will be published in the EPIC 2011 Proceedings.\r\n\r\nThe artifact itself should be transported to Boulder for the conference\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<b>Pecha</b><b> Kucha presentations</b>\r\n\r\nProposals Submission Deadline May 1, 2011<b></b>\r\n\r\nNow in our second year for this category, EPIC solicits Pecha Kucha (pronounced: \"peh-cha-ku-cha\'\') presentations. An informal, engaging and highly visual presentation of 20 slides, each one exactly 20 seconds, for a total presentation time of 6 minutes, 40 seconds. Pecha Kuchapresentations at EPIC are intended to communicate quickly and efficiently various ideas related to Ethnography <b>EVOLUTION / REVOLUTION</b>. We encourage submissions that are visually engaging, loaded with thought provoking content and provide a strong point of view on a specific topic related to the conference theme.\r\n\r\nSubmissions should include a single page describing the proposed Pecha Kucha concept; a brief 150-word description of the concept; and at least five slides which you intend to use as visuals in the presentation. This information should convey to reviewers what is the main point to be communicated and how it will be communicated.\r\n<blockquote>The deadline for Pecha Kucha proposal submissions is May 1, 2011.\r\n\r\nIn order to submit a proposal first <a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic/preGetID\">create an account</a> then log in to the <a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic\">EPIC submission and review system</a> to submit.</blockquote>\r\nNotification of acceptance will be sent by <b>June 5, 2011</b>. Accepted submissions will have their 150 word descriptions posted on the EPIC2011 website.\r\n\r\nIn case of acceptance, you will be required to present live to all EPIC2011 attendees.','Call for Participation','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision-v1','','','2014-02-06 16:53:41','2014-02-06 16:53:41','',4,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?p=10',0,'revision','',0),(11,1,'2014-02-09 21:22:53','2014-02-09 21:22:53','<strong>2014 Ethnographic Praxis in the Industry Conference (EPIC 2014), New York - September 7-10, 2014</strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\nBack in 2004, in a somewhat serendipitous encounter, two anthropologists from the industry realized the need for a forum to draw together their kinds and others as well. This was the inception of EPIC – the Ethnographic Praxis in the Industry Conference.\n\nTen years later, EPIC has become a conference that brings together a dynamic community of practitioners and scholars concerned with how ethnographic thinking, methods, and practices are used to transform design, business, and innovation settings and outcomes. Participants now come from innovation consultancies, design firms, universities and design schools, government and NGOs, research organizations, and corporations.  This call for papers focuses on the ways in which this community identifies, develops, and sustains relationships that create value or values.\n\nThere are two “sites” for this work, one nested in the other.  First, EPIC 2014 will be held in New York City (Sep 7-10), a place that welcomes multitudes of people, cultures, values, ideas. In NYC, proximity to different “others” has launched new relations that would never have been possible in singular and separate homogenized contexts. NYC is about the exchanges, powers, dreams, disillusions engendered by longstanding and complex business cultures and practices – from the Rockefellers to the NY Stock Exchange to the World Trade Center to the Freedom Tower. Second, the 2014 host of EPIC is the Center for Positive Marketing at Fordham University Business School. The Center recognizes the positive value exchange relationship between consumers and marketers, and encourages leveraging this relationship for mutual benefit to all.\n\nIn the midst of this, EPIC 2014 asks researchers and practitioners from different fields to explore the ways in which positive relations can lead to new beginnings and possibilities, or reestablish old ties. How can positive relations create new value or values in the things, places, and people with whom ethnographers engage?\n\nWe encourage paper submissions that frame the scope of value or values generated in methodological, theoretical, and business challenges, and the opportunities offered in empirical studies about the following topics:\n<ul>\n	<li>Social, cultural or institutional values in flux and the associated consequences</li>\n	<li>Values generated in co-creation and co-participation research</li>\n	<li>Our roles as change agents and triggers of transformation</li>\n	<li>Emerging practices such as, big data, lean, and agile: challenges and opportunities</li>\n	<li>Careers in flux: critical reflections on the shifting values of practitioner expertise</li>\n	<li>Reflections and projections on ethnography as EPIC enters its 10th year.</li>\n</ul>\nWe are looking forward to celebrating the 10th Anniversary of this great idea with you all in New York City. Please submit your ideas, experiences, research, what have you, and join us.\n\n<strong>Important Dates</strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>Submission of Extended-Abstract – March 14th, 2014</li>\n	<li>Acceptance notification – May 9th, 2014</li>\n	<li>Full paper draft  – June 13th, 2014</li>\n	<li>Final paper – August 27th, 2014</li>\n</ul>\nIn addition to Papers, EPIC 2014 will accept other types of submissions and participations: namely, Pecha-Kucha, Salons, Workshops, Doctoral &amp; Masters Colloquium, and Artifacts. More information about them will be sent out shortly.\n\n<strong>So, save the date</strong>\n\nAs you know, EPIC 2014 will be in New York on September 7-10, 2014. Are these dates in your calendar?\n<strong>Share the news</strong>\n\nOn twitter? Share your conversations by simply including this #EPIC2014 on your EPIC tweets!\n\nOn Facebook? Visit our page <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/epiconference\" target=\"_self\">here</a> and like it to stay up to date with the latest news.\nPlease help us spread the word, forward the call to anyone you think might be interested, like us on Facebook, tweet us... generally just \"activate those networks\".\n\nTill next time, your Co-chairs – Timothy Malefyt &amp; Rogério de Paula','Call For Papers','','inherit','open','open','','4-autosave-v1','','','2014-02-09 21:22:53','2014-02-09 21:22:53','',4,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?p=11',0,'revision','',0),(12,1,'2014-02-09 21:22:59','2014-02-09 21:22:59','<strong>2014 Ethnographic Praxis in the Industry Conference (EPIC 2014), New York - September 7-10, 2014</strong>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nBack in 2004, in a somewhat serendipitous encounter, two anthropologists from the industry realized the need for a forum to draw together their kinds and others as well. This was the inception of EPIC – the Ethnographic Praxis in the Industry Conference.\r\n\r\nTen years later, EPIC has become a conference that brings together a dynamic community of practitioners and scholars concerned with how ethnographic thinking, methods, and practices are used to transform design, business, and innovation settings and outcomes. Participants now come from innovation consultancies, design firms, universities and design schools, government and NGOs, research organizations, and corporations.  This call for papers focuses on the ways in which this community identifies, develops, and sustains relationships that create value or values.\r\n\r\nThere are two “sites” for this work, one nested in the other.  First, EPIC 2014 