ation settings and outcomes. Participants now come from innovation consultancies, design firms, universities and design schools, government and NGOs, research organizations, and corporations.  This call for papers focuses on the ways in which this community identifies, develops, and sustains relationships that create value or values.\r\n\r\nThere are two “sites” for this work, one nested in the other.  First, EPIC 2014 will be held in New York City (Sep 7-10), a place that welcomes multitudes of people, cultures, values, ideas. In NYC, proximity to different “others” has launched new relations that would never have been possible in singular and separate homogenized contexts. NYC is about the exchanges, powers, dreams, disillusions engendered by longstanding and complex business cultures and practices – from the Rockefellers to the NY Stock Exchange to the World Trade Center to the Freedom Tower. Second, the 2014 host of EPIC is the Center for Positive Marketing at Fordham University Business School. The Center recognizes the positive value exchange relationship between consumers and marketers, and encourages leveraging this relationship for mutual benefit to all.\r\n\r\nIn the midst of this, EPIC 2014 asks researchers and practitioners from different fields to explore the ways in which positive relations can lead to new beginnings and possibilities, or reestablish old ties. How can positive relations create new value or values in the things, places, and people with whom ethnographers engage?\r\n\r\nWe encourage paper submissions that frame the scope of value or values generated in methodological, theoretical, and business challenges, and the opportunities offered in empirical studies about the following topics:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Social, cultural or institutional values in flux and the associated consequences</li>\r\n	<li>Values generated in co-creation and co-participation research</li>\r\n	<li>Our roles as change agents and triggers of transformation</li>\r\n	<li>Emerging practices such as, big data, lean, and agile: challenges and opportunities</li>\r\n	<li>Careers in flux: critical reflections on the shifting values of practitioner expertise</li>\r\n	<li>Reflections and projections on ethnography as EPIC enters its 10th year.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe are looking forward to celebrating the 10th Anniversary of this great idea with you all in New York City. Please submit your ideas, experiences, research, what have you, and join us.\r\n<h3>Important Dates</h3>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Submission of Extended-Abstract – March 14th, 2014</li>\r\n	<li>Acceptance notification – May 9th, 2014</li>\r\n	<li>Full paper draft  – June 13th, 2014</li>\r\n	<li>Final paper – August 27th, 2014</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn addition to Papers, EPIC 2014 will accept other types of submissions and participations: namely, Pecha-Kucha, Salons, Workshops, Doctoral &amp; Masters Colloquium, and Artifacts. More information about them will be sent out shortly.\r\n<h3>So, save the date</h3>\r\nAs you know, EPIC 2014 will be in New York on September 7-10, 2014. Are these dates in your calendar?\r\n<h3>Share the news</h3>\r\nOn twitter? Share your conversations by simply including this #EPIC2014 on your EPIC tweets!\r\n\r\nOn Facebook? Visit our page <a href=\"https://www.facebook.com/epiconference\" target=\"_self\">here</a> and like it to stay up to date with the latest news.\r\nPlease help us spread the word, forward the call to anyone you think might be interested, like us on Facebook, tweet us... generally just \"activate those networks\".\r\n\r\nTill next time, your Co-chairs – Timothy Malefyt &amp; Rogério de Paula','Call For Papers','','inherit','open','open','','4-revision-v1','','','2014-02-09 21:28:43','2014-02-09 21:28:43','',4,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?p=17',0,'revision','',0),(18,1,'2014-02-09 21:29:10','2014-02-09 21:29:10','<h2>2014 Ethnographic Praxis in the Industry Conference (EPIC 2014), New York - September 7-10, 2014</h2>\r\nBack in 2004, 