 to explore the ways in which positive relations can lead to new beginnings and possibilities, or reestablish old ties. &lt;strong&gt;How can positive relations create new value or values in the things, places, and people with whom ethnographers engage?&lt;/strong&gt;\r\n\r\nWe encourage paper submissions that frame the scope of value or values generated in methodological, theoretical, and business challenges, and the opportunities offered in empirical studies. &lt;a title=\"Call for Participation\" href=\"http://localhost:8888/epic/?page_id=38\"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt;!','Home','','inherit','open','open','','43-revision-v1','','','2014-02-28 22:43:01','2014-02-28 22:43:01','',43,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?p=55',0,'revision','',0),(56,1,'2014-02-28 22:43:46','2014-02-28 22:43:46','EPIC 2014 asks researchers and practitioners from different fields to explore the ways in which positive relations can lead to new beginnings and possibilities, or reestablish old ties. &lt;strong&gt;How can positive relations create new value or values in the things, places, and people with whom ethnographers engage?&lt;/strong&gt;\r\n\r\nWe encourage paper submissions that frame the scope of value or values generated in methodological, theoretical, and business challenges, and the opportunities offered in empirical studies. &lt;a title=\"Call for Participation\" href=\"http://localhost:8888/epic/?page_id=38\"&gt;Learn more&lt;/a&gt;!','Home','','inherit','open','open','','43-revision-v1','','','2014-02-28 22:43:46','2014-02-28 22:43:46','',43,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?p=56',0,'revision','',0),(57,1,'2014-02-28 22:55:31','2014-02-28 22:55:31','<h2>2014 EPIC</h2>\r\n<strong>The deadline for Papers and Pecha-Kuchas has been extended to March 21st, 5PM PST.</strong>\r\n\r\nBack in 2004, in a somewhat serendipitous encounter, two anthropologists from the industry realized the need for a forum to draw together their kinds and others as well. This was the inception of EPIC—the Ethnographic Praxis in the Industry Conference.\r\n\r\nTen years later, EPIC has become a conference that brings together a dynamic community of practitioners and scholars concerned with how ethnographic thinking, methods, and practices are used to transform design, business, and innovation settings and outcomes. Participants now come from innovation consultancies, design firms, universities and design schools, government and NGOs, research organizations, and corporations. This call for papers focuses on the ways in which this community identifies, develops, and sustains relationships that create value or values.\r\n\r\nThere are two “sites” for this work, one nested in the other. First, EPIC 2014 will be held in New York City (Sept. 7-10), a place that welcomes multitudes of people, cultures, values, ideas. In NYC, proximity to different “others” has launched new relations that would never have been possible in singular and separate homogenized contexts. NYC is about the exchanges, powers, dreams, disillusions engendered by longstanding and complex business cultures and practices—from the Rockefellers to the NY Stock Exchange to the World Trade Center to the Freedom Tower. Second, the 2014 host of EPIC is the Center for Positive Marketing at Fordham University Business School. The Center recognizes the positive value exchange relationship between consumers and marketers, and encourages leveraging this relationship for mutual benefit to all.\r\n\r\nIn the midst of this, EPIC 2014 asks researchers and practitioners from different fields to explore the ways in which positive relations can lead to new beginnings and possibilities, or reestablish old ties. How can positive relations create new value or values in the things, places, and people with whom ethnographers engage?\r\n\r\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h3>PAPERS</h3>\r\n<div><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">We encourage paper submissions that frame the scope of value or values generated in methodological, theoretical, and business challenges, and the opportunities offered in empirical studies about the following topics:</span></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Social, cultural or institutional values in flux and the associated consequences</li>\r\n	<li>Values generated in co-creation and co-participation research</li>\r\n	<li>Our roles as change agents and triggers of transformation</li>\r\n	<li>Emerging practices such as, big data, lean, and agile: challenges and opportunities</li>\r\n	<li>Careers in flux: critical reflections on the shifting values of practitioner expertise</li>\r\n	<li>Reflections and projections on ethnography as EPIC enters its 10th year.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nPapers should present new perspectives, new developments, and new work within our practice whilst demonstrating the links between these new perspectives and existing literatures and debates. We encourage perspectives from diverse disciplinary backgrounds, such as, anthropology, informatics, design, and business.\r\n\r\nWe place a strong emphasis on presentation of the papers at the conference, aiming for the key ideas in the papers to be communicated in the most compelling and effective ways possible. Hence, we will request the final presentation to be reviewed and submitted prior to the conference.\r\n\r\n<b>Guidelines for Submission</b>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nFor the review process, you should submit an extended-abstract (not the final paper), including the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Anonymized submission in .docx or .pdf format</li>\r\n	<li>Title and outline of the full paper</li>\r\n	<li>The extended-abstract (&lt;750 words excluding references to relevant literature) describing the work/research, including (but not restricted to): objective, methods, study, and result discussion.</li>\r\n	<li>References to relevant literature or other types of previous work</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n<strong>Important Dates</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Submission of Extended-Abstract</strong> – <span style=\"color: #000000;\">*<strong>NEW*</strong> </span>March 21st (5PM PST)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"external-link\">Please upload your submission: <a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic/\">https://precisionconference.com/~epic/</a></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Acceptance notification</strong> – May 9th, 2014</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Full paper draft</strong> – June 13th, 2014</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Final paper</strong> – August 27th, 2014</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Review and Paper Preparation Procedure</b>\r\n\r\nThe extended-abstract submissions will be put through a double blind review process: namely, reviewers will not know who the authors are.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>To facilitate double-blind, the extended abstract should NOT contain any references to the author’s identity. Authors are thus encouraged to minimize references that may reveal their identities and their companies or institutions. Relevant references to an author’s previous research, or their organization’s products or services should not be suppressed but instead referenced in a neutral way, for example.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nImportant about accepted-paper submissions (after review process):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Authors of accepted extended-abstracts will be required to submit a full paper version by August 2014, which will be reviewed by a Curator over the Summer.</li>\r\n	<li>Accepted and presented papers will be published in the EPIC Proceedings.</li>\r\n	<li>Papers should not exceed 5000 words in length, excluding references.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nAny questions? Email: <a href=\"mailto:papers@epiconference.com\">papers@epiconference.com</a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h3>PECHA KUCHA</h3>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-151 alignright\" alt=\"PK_Logo\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/PK_Logo1-300x295.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"295\" data-id=\"151\" />\r\n\r\nPecha Kucha (pronounced: \"peh-cha-ku-cha\'\') presentations are a rapid-fire, engaging performance of 20 image-rich slides. Each slide shows for exactly 20 seconds before automatically moving to the next. Total presentation time is a speedy 6 minutes, 40 seconds. They are poetry delivered with a punch.\r\n\r\nWhen reviewing your abstracts, we look for the visual and verbal promise to surprise, provoke, evoke or simply take a stand. All submissions are blind-reviewed for originality, passion, point of view and relevance to the 2014 conference theme: exchange of value/values.\r\n\r\n<strong>Guidelines for Submission</strong>\r\n\r\nPlease submit a one page PDF or Word document that includes the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>500 words that briefly describe your overall concept as well as how your visual and verbal narratives will unfold</li>\r\n	<li>At least 5 images that you intend (and have the right permissions) to include as visuals for your presentation</li>\r\n	<li>Omit all references to your identity</li>\r\n	<li>Please do not submit additional documents</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"external-link\">By *<strong>NEW*</strong> March 21st (5PM PST), please upload your 1-2 page submission: <a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic/\">https://precisionconference.com/~epic/</a></div>\r\n<b>Other Important Dates:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Acceptance notification</strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> – May 9, 2014</span></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Pecha Kucha first draft</strong>  – July 20, 2014</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Print &amp; online proceedings final abstract</strong> – August, exact date tbd</li>\r\n	<li><strong style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Final Pecha Kucha</strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> – August 27, 2014</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAny questions? Email: <a title=\"pechakucha@epiconference.com\" href=\"mailto: pechakucha@epiconference.com\">pechakucha@epiconference.com</a>\r\n\r\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h3>SALONS</h3>\r\nSalons are associated with the literary and philosophical movements of the 18th Century Enlightenment. At EPIC 2014, we will grow the format (initiated last year) by gathering small groups of people, in intimate settings, with inspiring hosts – to engage in lively conversation on inspiring topics.\r\n\r\nSalons were born from a lack of “horizontal” talking space at EPIC, or (in plain English) their purpose is to give attendees more room to have conversations that are ‘on topic,’ but where they are not being “presented to” or workshopped by experts (or panels) who hold the floor.\r\n\r\n<strong>Themes</strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">We invite submissions that tackle the conference theme, the exchange of value/values, and that come from across the EPIC community – from researchers to designers to policy makers and more; from first-time EPIC-goers to those who attended them all.  Possible themes include:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Social, cultural or institutional values in flux and the associated consequences</li>\r\n	<li>Values generated in co-creation and co-participation research</li>\r\n	<li>Our roles as change agents and triggers of transformation</li>\r\n	<li>Emerging practices such as, big data, lean, and agile: challenges and opportunities</li>\r\n	<li>Careers in flux: critical reflections on the shifting values of practitioner expertise</li>\r\n	<li>Reflections and projections on ethnography as EPIC enters its 10th year</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Salon Format</strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">At their simplest, Salons are loosely-guided group discussions, for which </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">we are now inviting you to play a Host that loosely guides</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">. Because, as hinted earlier, the Salons we want to stage can most clearly be defined as a series of ‘Nots’:  </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><i>not a seminar, not a presentation, nor a workshop.</i></b>\r\n\r\n<b>If you accept this challenge</b>, it will be your job to ensure that these sessions are instead multi-vocal conversations, with no agenda (or goal to be reached) beyond a stimulating exploration of your chosen topic. As host, we will also ask you to invite one selected Discussant to help you prime the conversation. But <b>our expectation is that all participants will contribute to the Salon on an equal footing.</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Please contact us with your idea for hosting a Salon.</b> The deadline is<b> March, 30<sup>th</sup></b>\r\n\r\nAny questions? Email: <a title=\"salons@epiconference.com\" href=\"mailto: salons@epiconference.com\">salons@epiconference.com</a>\r\n\r\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h3><b>THE AUTHORS\' SPACE <span style=\"color: #597380;\">(NEW AT EPIC)</span></b></h3>\r\n<b></b>At EPIC we continually strive to provide relevance for our community, keep us connected through ideas and approaches from each other’s work, and inform attendees of the latest in praxis, thought leadership and innovative approaches to our work, in and out of industry. The idea of the authors’ space is to provide a physical location where recent authors can show their books and chat about them with EPIC attendees. The current plan is for EPIC to provide a large table where authors can showcase their books, sign them if desired, and talk with whoever shows up. Depending on the response, we might have authors rotate into the space maybe for two hours, after which time a different author would rotate in. We’d post a schedule with times, authors’ names, and book titles.\r\n\r\nTo be part of this experimental effort this year we are going to showcase only recent books (published no earlier than 2010) of interest to the EPIC community, by authors who will be present at the conference, and have been connected to EPIC in a significant way. If you are an author who has presented a paper or workshop, or been involved in the EPIC review process or have done volunteer work or committee work, or shown commitment to EPIC in some other way – EPIC would like to enable you to showcase your book at EPIC2014.\r\n\r\nWe would encourage authors to not only bring a stack of fliers with them (there will be a pin-up wall for that) but also a number of their books, which they are willing to sell. Sales will be up to each individual author. EPIC (the organization) will not be involved in any financial transactions. If you wish to have your book considered for the authors’ space, please send us the title with publication data, together with a few lines responding to the criteria listed above. Submit by <strong>April 30</strong> to Gitti Jordan (<a href=\"mailto:gitti.jordan@gmail.com\">gitti.jordan@gmail.com</a>).\r\n\r\nWe welcome your comments and suggestions for helping us make this a success. Please feel free to circulate the information about this exciting new opportunity for the authors and attendees at EPIC2014.\r\n\r\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h3><b>Doctoral and Masters Colloquium</b></h3>\r\nThe Doctoral and Masters Colloquium is a day-long forum where PhD and Masters students engaged in supervised thesis research meet to discuss their research, present issues of concern to them, and receive feedback from a panel of experienced EPIC researchers and practitioners as well as other student participants. We welcome applicants from a broad range of disciplines, including anthropology, sociology, cognitive science, design science, organizational studies, and related fields. Applicants’ research should involve the application of ethnographic theory and method in the context of business and industry (both for profit and not for profit). Enrollment is limited to approximately 15 students and selection will be based on the overall quality of the application and relevance to the EPIC mission of promoting the integration of social and cultural perspectives, theory, and method into business and organizational practice. Participants will be expected to give short, informal presentations of their doctoral or masters research during the Colloquium, to be followed by discussion.\r\n\r\nApplications to participate in the Colloquium should include the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A 2-3 page overview of your doctoral or masters research, including a statement of your research problem or rationale, research questions and methods, the status of current work, and expected contributions to your field of interest.</li>\r\n	<li>Your intended career objectives as you envision them at this point (these may be either academic or practice-related).</li>\r\n	<li>A paragraph that describes what you hope to gain from attending the EPIC Doctoral and Masters Colloquium.</li>\r\n	<li>A short (1-2 paragraph) biographical sketch.</li>\r\n	<li>Optional:  Letter of recommendation from a research mentor or advisor.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"external-link\">Please submit proposals through <a href=\"mailto:colloquium@epiconference.com\">colloquium@epiconference.com</a></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Submission deadline – May 11th</li>\r\n	<li>Notification of provisional acceptance – June 9th</li>\r\n	<li>Colloquium - September 7th</li>\r\n</ul>','Call for Participation','','publish','closed','closed','','call-for-participation-2','','','2014-03-17 16:54:08','2014-03-17 16:54:08','',0,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?page_id=57',0,'page','',0),(58,1,'2014-02-28 22:55:31','2014-02-28 22:55:31','&lt;h2&gt;2014 EPIC&lt;/h2&gt;\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;Back in 2004, in a somewhat serendipitous encounter, two anthropologists from the industry realized the need for a forum to draw together their kinds and others as well. This was the inception of EPIC—the Ethnographic Praxis in the Industry Conference. &lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;Ten years later, EPIC has become a conference that brings together a dynamic community of practitioners and scholars concerned with how ethnographic thinking, methods, and practices are used to transform design, business, and innovation settings and outcomes. Participants now come from innovation consultancies, design firms, universities and design schools, government and NGOs, research organizations, and corporations. This call for papers focuses on the ways in which this community identifies, develops, and sustains relationships that create value or values. &lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;There are two “sites” for this work, one nested in the other. First, EPIC 2014 will be held in New York City (Sept. 7-10), a place that welcomes multitudes of people, cultures, values, ideas. In NYC, proximity to different “others” has launched new relations that would never have been possible in singular and separate homogenized contexts. NYC is about the exchanges, powers, dreams, disillusions engendered by longstanding and complex business cultures and practices—from the Rockefellers to the NY Stock Exchange to the World Trade Center to the Freedom Tower. Second, the 2014 host of EPIC is the Center for Positive Marketing at Fordham University Business School. The Center recognizes the positive value exchange relationship between consumers and marketers, and encourages leveraging this relationship for mutual benefit to all. &lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;In the midst of this, EPIC 2014 asks researchers and practitioners from different fields to explore the ways in which positive relations can lead to new beginnings and possibilities, or reestablish old ties. How can positive relations create new value or values in the things, places, and people with whom ethnographers engage?&lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;h3&gt;PAPERS&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;We encourage paper submissions that frame the scope of value or values generated in methodological, theoretical, and business challenges, and the opportunities offered in empirical studies about the following topics: &lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Social, cultural or institutional values in flux and the associated consequences&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Values generated in co-creation and co-participation research&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Our roles as change agents and triggers of transformation&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Emerging practices such as, big data, lean, and agile: challenges and opportunities&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Careers in flux: critical reflections on the shifting values of practitioner expertise&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Reflections and projections on ethnography as EPIC enters its 10th year.&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;We are looking forward to celebrating the 10th Anniversary of this great idea with you all in New York City. Please submit your ideas, experiences, research, what have you, and join us.&lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;&lt;strong&gt;IMPORTANT DATES&lt;/strong&gt; &lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Submission of Extended-Abstract&lt;/strong&gt; – March 14th, 2014&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;div class=\"external-link\"&gt;Please upload your one page submission: &lt;a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic/\"&gt;https://precisionconference.com/~epic/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acceptance notification&lt;/strong&gt; – May 9th, 2014&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Full paper draft&lt;/strong&gt; – June 13th, 2014&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Final paper&lt;/strong&gt; – August 27th, 2014&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\nIn addition to Papers, EPIC 2014 will accept other types of submissions and participations: namely, Salons, Workshops, Doctoral &amp;amp; Masters Colloquium, and Artifacts. More information about them will be sent out shortly.\r\n&lt;h3&gt;Pecha Kucha&lt;/h3&gt;\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;Pecha Kucha (pronounced: \"peh-cha-ku-cha\'\') presentations are a rapid-fire, engaging performance of 20 image-rich slides. Each slide shows for exactly 20 seconds before automatically moving to the next. Total presentation time is a speedy 6 minutes, 40 seconds. They are poetry delivered with a punch. &lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;When reviewing your abstracts, we look for the visual and verbal promise to surprise, provoke, evoke or simply take a stand. All submissions are blind-reviewed for originality, passion, point of view and relevance to the 2014 conference theme: exchange of value/values. &lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;Guidelines for submission: &lt;/span&gt;\r\n\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;Please submit a one page PDF or Word document that includes the following: • 500 words that briefly describe your overall concept as well as how your visual  and verbal narratives will unfold &lt;/span&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;At least 5 images that you intend (and have the right permissions) to include as  visuals for your presentation&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Omit all references to your identity&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;Please do not submit additional documents&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;strong&gt;&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;IMPORTANT DATES&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/strong&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Abstract Submission&lt;/strong&gt; – March 14, 2014&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;div class=\"external-link\"&gt;Please upload your one page submission: &lt;a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic/\"&gt;https://precisionconference.com/~epic/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;\r\n&lt;ul&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Acceptance notification&lt;/strong&gt; – May 9, 2014&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Pecha Kucha first draft&lt;/strong&gt; – July 20, 2014 • Print &amp;amp; online proceedings final abstract – August, exact date tbd&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Final Pecha Kucha&lt;/strong&gt; – August 27, 2014 Any questions?&lt;/li&gt;\r\n&lt;/ul&gt;\r\n&lt;span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"&gt;Email &lt;a href=\"mailto:PechaKucha@epiconference.com\"&gt;PechaKucha@epiconference.com&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/span&gt;','Call for Participation','','inherit','open','open','','57-revision-v1','','','2014-02-28 22:55:31','2014-02-28 22:55:31','',57,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?p=58',0,'revision','',0),(59,1,'2014-02-28 22:56:00','2014-02-28 22:56:00','<img class=\"alignnone size-full wp-image-72\" alt=\"Venue1\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/Venue1.png\" width=\"650\" height=\"425\" data-id=\"72\" />There are two “sites” for this work, one nested in the other. First, EPIC 2014 will be held in New York City (Sep 7-10), a place that welcomes multitudes of people, cultures, values, ideas. In NYC, proximity to different “others” has launched new relations that would never have been possible in singular and separate homogenized contexts. NYC is about the exchanges, powers, dreams, disillusions engendered by longstanding and complex business cultures and practices—from the Rockefellers to the NY Stock Exchange to the World Trade Center to the Freedom Tower. Second, the 2014 host of EPIC is the Center for Positive Marketing at Fordham University Business School. The Center recognizes the positive value exchange relationship between consumers and marketers, and encourages leveraging this relationship for mutual benefit to all.\r\n<h3>The Center for