hange agents and triggers of transformation</li>\r\n	<li>Emerging practices such as, big data, lean, and agile: challenges and opportunities</li>\r\n	<li>Careers in flux: critical reflections on the shifting values of practitioner expertise</li>\r\n	<li>Reflections and projections on ethnography as EPIC enters its 10th year.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nPapers should present new perspectives, new developments, and new work within our practice whilst demonstrating the links between these new perspectives and existing literatures and debates. We encourage perspectives from diverse disciplinary backgrounds, such as, anthropology, informatics, design, and business.\r\n\r\nWe place a strong emphasis on presentation of the papers at the conference, aiming for the key ideas in the papers to be communicated in the most compelling and effective ways possible. Hence, we will request the final presentation to be reviewed and submitted prior to the conference.\r\n\r\n<b>Guidelines for Submission</b>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nFor the review process, you should submit an extended-abstract (not the final paper), including the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Anonymized submission in .docx or .pdf format</li>\r\n	<li>Title and outline of the full paper</li>\r\n	<li>The extended-abstract (&lt;750 words excluding references to relevant literature) describing the work/research, including (but not restricted to): objective, methods, study, and result discussion.</li>\r\n	<li>References to relevant literature or other types of previous work</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\n<strong>Important Dates</strong>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Submission of Extended-Abstract</strong> – March 14th, 2014</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"external-link\">Please upload your submission: <a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic/\">https://precisionconference.com/~epic/</a></div>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Acceptance notification</strong> – May 9th, 2014</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Full paper draft</strong> – June 13th, 2014</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Final paper</strong> – August 27th, 2014</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<b>Review and Paper Preparation Procedure</b>\r\n\r\nThe extended-abstract submissions will be put through a double blind review process: namely, reviewers will not know who the authors are.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<div>To facilitate double-blind, the extended abstract should NOT contain any references to the author’s identity. Authors are thus encouraged to minimize references that may reveal their identities and their companies or institutions. Relevant references to an author’s previous research, or their organization’s products or services should not be suppressed but instead referenced in a neutral way, for example.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nImportant about accepted-paper submissions (after review process):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Authors of accepted extended-abstracts will be required to submit a full paper version by August 2014, which will be reviewed by a Curator over the Summer.</li>\r\n	<li>Accepted and presented papers will be published in the EPIC Proceedings.</li>\r\n	<li>Papers should not exceed 5000 words in length, excluding references.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</div>\r\n<div>\r\n\r\nAny questions? Email: <a href=\"mailto:papers@epiconference.com\">papers@epiconference.com</a>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h3>PECHA KUCHA</h3>\r\n<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-151 alignright\" alt=\"PK_Logo\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/PK_Logo1-300x295.png\" width=\"300\" height=\"295\" data-id=\"151\" />\r\n\r\nPecha Kucha (pronounced: \"peh-cha-ku-cha\'\') presentations are a rapid-fire, engaging performance of 20 image-rich slides. Each slide shows for exactly 20 seconds before automatically moving to the next. Total presentation time is a speedy 6 minutes, 40 seconds. They are poetry delivered with a punch.\r\n\r\nWhen reviewing your abstracts, we look for the visual and verbal promise to surprise, provoke, evoke or simply take a stand. All submissions are blind-reviewed for originality, passion, point of view and relevance to the 2014 conference theme: exchange of value/values.\r\n\r\n<strong>Guidelines for Submission</strong>\r\n\r\nPlease submit a one page PDF or Word document that includes the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>500 words that briefly describe your overall concept as well as how your visual and verbal narratives will unfold</li>\r\n	<li>At least 5 images that you intend (and have the right permissions) to include as visuals for your presentation</li>\r\n	<li>Omit all references to your identity</li>\r\n	<li>Please do not submit additional documents</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div class=\"external-link\">By <strong>March 14</strong>, please upload your 1-2 page submission: <a href=\"https://precisionconference.com/~epic/\">https://precisionconference.com/~epic/</a></div>\r\n<b>Other Important Dates:</b>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Abstract submission</strong> – March 14, 2014</li>\r\n	<li><strong style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Acceptance notification</strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> – May 9, 2014</span></li>\r\n	<li><strong>Pecha Kucha first draft</strong>  – July 20, 2014</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Print &amp; online proceedings final abstract</strong> – August, exact date tbd</li>\r\n	<li><strong style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">Final Pecha Kucha</strong><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"> – August 27, 2014</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAny questions? Email: <a title=\"pechakucha@epiconference.com\" href=\"mailto: pechakucha@epiconference.com\">pechakucha@epiconference.com</a>\r\n\r\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h3>SALONS</h3>\r\nSalons are associated with the literary and philosophical movements of the 18th Century Enlightenment. At EPIC 2014, we will grow the format (initiated last year) by gathering small groups of people, in intimate settings, with inspiring hosts – to engage in lively conversation on inspiring topics.\r\n\r\nSalons were born from a lack of “horizontal” talking space at EPIC, or (in plain English) their purpose is to give attendees more room to have conversations that are ‘on topic,’ but where they are not being “presented to” or workshopped by experts (or panels) who hold the floor.\r\n\r\n<strong>Themes</strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">We invite submissions that tackle the conference theme, the exchange of value/values, and that come from across the EPIC community – from researchers to designers to policy makers and more; from first-time EPIC-goers to those who attended them all.  Possible themes include:</span>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Social, cultural or institutional values in flux and the associated consequences</li>\r\n	<li>Values generated in co-creation and co-participation research</li>\r\n	<li>Our roles as change agents and triggers of transformation</li>\r\n	<li>Emerging practices such as, big data, lean, and agile: challenges and opportunities</li>\r\n	<li>Careers in flux: critical reflections on the shifting values of practitioner expertise</li>\r\n	<li>Reflections and projections on ethnography as EPIC enters its 10th year</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<strong>Salon Format</strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">At their simplest, Salons are loosely-guided group discussions, for which </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">we are now inviting you to play a Host that loosely guides</b><span style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\">. Because, as hinted earlier, the Salons we want to stage can most clearly be defined as a series of ‘Nots’:  </span><b style=\"line-height: 1.5em;\"><i>not a seminar, not a presentation, nor a workshop.</i></b>\r\n\r\n<b>If you accept this challenge</b>, it will be your job to ensure that these sessions are instead multi-vocal conversations, with no agenda (or goal to be reached) beyond a stimulating exploration of your chosen topic. As host, we will also ask that you invite two or three selected Discussants to help you prime the conversation. But <b>our expectation is that all participants will contribute to the Salon on an equal footing.</b>\r\n\r\n<b>Please contact us with your idea for hosting a Salon.</b> The deadline is<b> March, 30<sup>th</sup></b>\r\n\r\nAny questions? Email: <a title=\"salons@epiconference.com\" href=\"mailto: salons@epiconference.com\">salons@epiconference.com</a>\r\n\r\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h3><b>THE AUTHORS\' SPACE <span style=\"color: #597380;\">(NEW AT EPIC)</span></b></h3>\r\n<b></b>At EPIC we continually strive to provide relevance for our community, keep us connected through ideas and approaches from each other’s work, and inform attendees of the latest in praxis, thought leadership and innovative approaches to our work, in and out of industry. The idea of the authors’ space is to provide a physical location where recent authors can show their books and chat about them with EPIC attendees. The current plan is for EPIC to provide a large table where authors can showcase their books, sign them if desired, and talk with whoever shows up. Depending on the response, we might have authors rotate into the space maybe for two hours, after which time a different author would rotate in. We’d post a schedule with times, authors’ names, and book titles.\r\n\r\nTo be part of this experimental effort this year we are going to showcase only recent books (published no earlier than 2010) of interest to the EPIC community, by authors who will be present at the conference, and have been connected to EPIC in a significant way. If you are an author who has presented a paper or workshop, or been involved in the EPIC review process or have done volunteer work or committee work, or shown commitment to EPIC in some other way – EPIC would like to enable you to showcase your book at EPIC2014.\r\n\r\nWe would encourage authors to not only bring a stack of fliers with them (there will be a pin-up wall for that) but also a number of their books, which they are willing to sell. Sales will be up to each individual author. EPIC (the organization) will not be involved in any financial transactions. If you wish to have your book considered for the authors’ space, please send us the title with publication data, together with a few lines responding to the criteria listed above. Submit by <strong>April 30</strong> to Gitti Jordan (<a href=\"mailto:gitti.jordan@gmail.com\">gitti.jordan@gmail.com</a>).\r\n\r\nWe welcome your comments and suggestions for helping us make this a success. Please feel free to circulate the information about this exciting new opportunity for the authors and attendees at EPIC2014.','Call for Participation','','inherit','open','open','','57-revision-v1','','','2014-03-12 16:17:06','2014-03-12 16:17:06','',57,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?p=156',0,'revision','',0),(157,1,'2014-05-05 14:16:37','2014-05-05 14:16:37','<h2>2014 EPIC</h2>\r\n<strong>The deadline for Papers and Pecha-Kuchas has been extended to March 21st, 5PM PST.</strong>\r\n\r\nBack in 2004, in a somewhat serendipitous encounter, two anthropologists from the industry realized the need for a forum to draw together their kinds and others as well. This was the inception of EPIC—the Ethnographic Praxis in the Industry Conference.\r\n\r\nTen years later, EPIC has become a conference that brings together a dynamic community of practitioners and scholars concerned with how ethnographic thinking, methods, and practices are used to transform design, business, and innovation settings and outcomes. Participants now come from innovation consultancies, design firms, universities and design schools, government and NGOs, research organizations, and corporations. This call for papers focuses on the ways