">Katharine Sieck, Olsen Marketing</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Exploring the Intangible Potential of the Private Energy User in the Emergent Design of an Electricity Smart Grid\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Louise Buch Løgstrup, SPIRE, University of Southern Denmark; Maren Melissa Nelson-Burk, Wafa Said Mosleh, Wendy Gunn (SPIRE, The Southern University of Denmark)</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Mobility is more than a device: understanding complexity in healthcare with ethnography\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Anna Wojnarowska, Experientia; Nancy Vuckovic, Intel; Todd Harple, Intel; Gina Taha, Experientia</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Ethnographic Findings in the Organizational Theater\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Jacob Buur, Rosa Torguet, SPIRE, University of Southern Denmark</div>\r\n[expand title=\"“Out of the labs”: The role for ethnography in guiding clinical trials\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Yosha Gargeya, Mads Holme, ReD Associates</div>','Schedule: Wednesday 10, 2014','','inherit','open','open','','557-revision-v1','','','2014-05-02 21:13:41','2014-05-02 21:13:41','',557,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/557-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(596,1,'2014-05-03 01:25:26','2014-05-03 01:25:26','EPIC 2014 asks researchers and practitioners from different fields to explore the ways in which positive relations can lead to new beginnings and possibilities, or reestablish old ties. How can positive relations create new value or values in the things, places, and people with whom ethnographers engage?','Home','','inherit','open','open','','188-revision-v1','','','2014-05-03 01:25:26','2014-05-03 01:25:26','',188,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/188-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(600,1,'2014-05-27 14:46:13','2014-05-27 14:46:13','<h5>9:30-12:30</h5>\r\n<h4>Workshops</h4>\r\n[expand title=\"Consumer Social Responsibility\"]This seminar-format workshop is aimed at exploring the consumer\'s role in shaping the social environment and focuses on demand-side issues of social responsibility. Participants of the workshop will draw on and share their own consumer behavior (a paragraph prepared prior to the workshop) to explore issues such as the trade-off between individual consumer value and societal value, consumer response to corporate social (ir)responsibility, and avenues to promote more socially responsible consumption. Participants will use their material to discuss balancing socially responsible consumption and employ a follow up tool – V-Positive – to provide input for specific brands and consumer responses.[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by Luke Kachersky, Assistant Professor of Marketing, Fordham.</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"Explorations: Creativity and Magic at Work\"]Politicians, corporate executives, civil servants, and academics talk about “creative industries,” “creative hubs” (or clusters), “creative cities,” “creative classes,” assigning high cultural prestige to what were previously mundane business activities. Yet, the words “creative” and “creativity” are pushed aside and treated as existing in a well-cushioned vacuum. All that is required to nourish creativity, it seems, are the right kinds of people gathered in the right kinds of spaces doing the right kinds of creative activity. In this sense, most people in business, education, and political administration appear to believe in creativity as a form of “magic”.\r\nThis workshop seeks to answer the question: “what is creativity?” To do this, it looks at a number of different case studies of creativity at work (a ceramic art exhibition, an advertising campaign, editing a woman’s fashion magazine). Is creativity no more than cultural bricolage, based on the past experiences of those involved? Or is it possible for those working in business situations to come up with genuinely creative innovations? If so, what facilitates and what hinders them? And what are the different values and types of evaluation (technical, social, aesthetic, financial, and so on) brought to bear by the different people working together on a project (design, advertising, fashion, film, and so on)? In other words, how is the meaning of creativity negotiated?\r\nParticipants are invited to bring their own ethnographic experiences to bear as we explore creativity at work in different business contexts. In particular, they will be asked to reflect on their ethnographic practices and experiences. How, as consultants, can they contribute to a client’s creative environment?\r\n<em><strong>Workshop Outcomes</strong></em> By attending this workshop, participants will gain an understanding of:\r\n	•	What creativity is and how it works in practice in different business situations;\r\n	•	The different kinds of values that different people involved bring to bear on the creative process as they negotiate their individual meanings of “creativity”;\r\n	•	How best to apply these insights to their own research practices.\r\n[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by Brian Moeran- Editor, <em>Journal of Business Anthropology</em>, Copenhagen Business School/Univeristy of Hong Kong</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n[expand title=\" Toward Conceptual, Methodological, and Ethical Standards of Practice in Business Anthropology\"]Ed ut perspiciatis unde omnis iste natus error sit voluptatem accusantium doloremque laudantium, totam rem aperiam, eaque ipsa quae ab illo inventore veritatis et quasi architecto beatae vitae dicta sunt explicabo. Nemo enim ipsam voluptatem quia voluptas sit aspernatur aut odit aut fugit, sed quia consequuntur magni dolores eos qui ratione voluptatem sequi nesciunt.[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Theodore Pollari, Kim Erwin, IIT Institute of Design</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"Big Data or ‘Big Ethnographic Data\'? Positioning Big Data within the ethnographic space\"]The rapid growth of business anthropology over the last decades and the adoption of ethnography by numerous professionals in a variety of industries, some trained, some not, suggests the importance of defining the character of business anthropology, so that as anthropology is increasingly adopted outside the academic world it continues to maintain distinctive content and high standards of practice. Historically, the structure of authority in anthropology was clear and monolithic with academic institutions defining the field. Today, a majority of anthropologists are pursuing their profession outside the academic world, increasingly in business. Concurrently, many non-anthropologists have engaged in business anthropology, especially ethnography. At this historical juncture it would be beneficial to have a statement defining the educational, conceptual, and methodological foundations of the field that emanated from qualified business anthropologists. This workshop is an initial step in an ongoing discussion of the character of business anthropology, ultimately leading to some document that expresses standards for the field.\r\nStandards in themselves can be either aspirational or demarcational: they can either present something for the larger community to aspire to, or they can be used to draw boundaries distinguishing legitimate practitioners from others. Mature professions, such as law, medicine, architecture, and engineering, have established their professional identities, combining academic preparation, board certification, and state licensure: these are typically the result of numerous years of discussion and negotiation. For the present, within anthropology, it is important not to draw boundaries between what is and is not business anthropology, but rather to hold up models of excellence that practitioners might aspire to, and to create a shared understanding of educational, methodological, and ethical foundations.\r\nThe workshop will have four objectives or questions to be answered:\r\n	•	Should there be ongoing discussion and perhaps codification of the educational, methodological, and ethical foundations or standards of business anthropology?\r\n	•	If so, what is the substantive content such an intiative, and how broadly should foundations and/or standards be defined?\r\n	•	How, where and when should foundations and/or standards be presented?   Do they need to be adopted by a professional society?  Which one?\r\n	•	What is the best means for building a network for propagating these practices?\r\n\r\nWorkshop participants will be given required readings that will inform their discussion. The exact content of the workshop will combine general discussion, ideation, and possibly two or three breakout groups to work on specific issues.  It will conclude with crafting a draft statement of principles.   [/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by Allen Batteau, Associate Professor, Wayne St. U. Detroit and Robert Morais, Principle of Weinman, Schnee, Morais, Inc.</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"What We Talk About When We Talk Data: Metrics, Mobilization, and Materiality in Performing Health Online, Department of Communication\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n\r\n\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Brittany Fiore, Silfvast; Gina Neff (University of Washington)</div>\r\n[expand title=\"From Street to Satellite: Mixing Methods To Understand Mobile Money Users Erin Taylor, Institute for Social Sciences\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Heather Horst (Royal Melbourne Institute of Technology)</div>\r\n\r\n\r\n<img src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" alt=\"rule\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n\r\n<h5>13:30 to 14:50</h5>\r\n<h4>Pecha Kucha</h4>\r\n[expand title=\"Daily Ordinary Joy\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Paul Ratliff</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Consider Everything\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">J. Paul Neeley, Neeley Worldwide</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Your Creative Mindset Is the Future\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Shilpi Kumar, Herman Miller; Keta Patel, Paul Sheetz, Chia-Ling Yu, IIT Institute of Design</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Snore: Public Sleeping in China\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Molly Stevens, Google</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Trust Me\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Han Pham, Intel Labs Europe</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Behind Bars\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Becky Rowe, ESRO</div>\r\n<img src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" alt=\"rule\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\r\n<h5>15:40 to 17:20</h5>\r\n<h4>Paper Session 2</h4>\r\n[expand title=\"Facing complexity\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Stefana Broadbent, University College London</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Move Me: On Stories, Rituals, and Building Brand Communities\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Katharine Sieck, Olsen Marketing</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Exploring the Intangible Potential of the Private Energy User in the Emergent Design of an Electricity Smart Grid\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Louise Buch Løgstrup, SPIRE, University of Southern Denmark; Maren Melissa Nelson-Burk, Wafa Said Mosleh, Wendy Gunn (SPIRE, The Southern University of Denmark)</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Mobility is more than a device: understanding complexity in healthcare with ethnography\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Anna Wojnarowska, Experientia; Nancy Vuckovic, Intel; Todd Harple, Intel; Gina Taha, Experientia</div>\r\n[expand title=\"Ethnographic Findings in the Organizational Theater\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Jacob Buur, Rosa Torguet, SPIRE, University of Southern Denmark</div>\r\n[expand title=\"“Out of the labs”: The role for ethnography in guiding clinical trials\"]Expanded Content[/expand]\r\n<div clas