 creativity as a form of “magic”.\r\n\r\nThis workshop seeks to answer the question: “what is creativity?” To do this, it looks at a number of different case studies of creativity at work (a ceramic art exhibition, an advertising campaign, editing a woman’s fashion magazine). Is creativity no more than cultural bricolage, based on the past experiences of those involved? Or is it possible for those working in business situations to come up with genuinely creative innovations? If so, what facilitates and what hinders them? And what are the different values and types of evaluation (technical, social, aesthetic, financial, and so on) brought to bear by the different people working together on a project (design, advertising, fashion, film, and so on)? In other words, how is the meaning of creativity negotiated?\r\n\r\nParticipants are invited to bring their own ethnographic experiences to bear as we explore creativity at work in different business contexts. In particular, they will be asked to reflect on their ethnographic practices and experiences. How, as consultants, can they contribute to a client’s creative environment?\r\n<em><strong>Workshop Outcomes</strong></em> By attending this workshop, participants will gain an understanding of:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>What creativity is and how it works in practice in different business situations;</li>\r\n	<li>The different kinds of values that different people involved bring to bear on the creative process as they negotiate their individual meanings of “creativity”;</li>\r\n	<li>How best to apply these insights to their own research practices.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Brian Moeran</strong>, Editor, <em>Journal of Business Anthropology</em>, Copenhagen Business School/Univeristy of Hong Kong </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"Toward Conceptual, Methodological, and Ethical Standards of Practice in Business Anthropology\"]The rapid growth of business anthropology over the last decades and the adoption of ethnography by numerous professionals in a variety of industries, some trained, some not, suggests the importance of defining the character of business anthropology, so that as anthropology is increasingly adopted outside the academic world it continues to maintain distinctive content and high standards of practice. Historically, the structure of authority in anthropology was clear and monolithic with academic institutions defining the field. Today, a majority of anthropologists are pursuing their profession outside the academic world, increasingly in business. Concurrently, many non-anthropologists have engaged in business anthropology, especially ethnography. At this historical juncture it would be beneficial to have a statement defining the educational, conceptual, and methodological foundations of the field that emanated from qualified business anthropologists. This workshop is an initial step in an ongoing discussion of the character of business anthropology, ultimately leading to some document that expresses standards for the field.\r\n\r\nStandards in themselves can be either aspirational or demarcational: they can either present something for the larger community to aspire to, or they can be used to draw boundaries distinguishing legitimate practitioners from others. Mature professions, such as law, medicine, architecture, and engineering, have established their professional identities, combining academic preparation, board certification, and state licensure: these are typically the result of numerous years of discussion and negotiation. For the present, within anthropology, it is important not to draw boundaries between what is and is not business anthropology, but rather to hold up models of excellence that practitioners might aspire to, and to create a shared understanding of educational, methodological, and ethical foundations.\r\n\r\nThe workshop will have four objectives or questions to be answered:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Should there be ongoing discussion and perhaps codification of the educational, methodological, and ethical foundations or standards of business anthropology?</li>\r\n	<li>If so, what is the substantive content such an intiative, and how broadly should foundations and/or standards be defined?</li>\r\n	<li>How, where and when should foundations and/or standards be presented? Do they need to be adopted by a professional society? Which one?</li>\r\n	<li>What is the best means for building a network for propagating these practices?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWorkshop participants will be given required readings that will inform their discussion. The exact content of the workshop will combine general discussion, ideation, and possibly two or three breakout groups to work on specific issues. It will conclude with crafting a draft statement of principles. [/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Allen Batteau</strong>, Associate Professor, Wayne St. U. Detroit ; <strong>Robert Morais</strong>, Principle of Weinman, Schnee, Morais, Inc. </div>\r\n\r\n<h5><strong>Afternoon Session:</strong> 1:30-4:30</h5>\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"You too can collect “big data”! How to combine quant and qual data to create a holistic picture of your users.\"]\r\nThere is much interest in the topic of Big Data. However, many researchers are unclear how to combine rich or “thick,” ethnographic data with large-scale quantitative data. This workshop offers an approach, which does not require a computer science degree: ESM via PACO. Experiential Sampling Methodology (ESM) is a type of longitudinal diary study that allows one to understand a person’s experience in the moment. Using a free, open-source mobile app called “PACO (Personal Analytics Companion),” we can conduct large-scale ESM studies with users anywhere in the world. These studies can be conducted after ethnographic studies to ascertain how broadly your observations apply to your user population or they can be done in advance to identify insights you want to study in-person, in-depth.  By combining these methodologies, you create a more holistic understanding of your users.\r\n\r\nIn this three-hour workshop, we will introduce attendees to ESM, discuss ways we have used this methodology at Google, help attendees create their own ESM study, and discuss data analysis. The goal is for every attendee to leave the session equipped with the knowledge to design and create their own ESM study, analyze the data, and make actionable recommendations.  Attendance will be capped at 25 attendees to ensure 1:1 attention and good group discussions.\r\n[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Anna Avrekh</strong>, User Experience Researcher at Google for 9+ years;<strong> Kathy Baxter</strong>, Google Staff User Experience Researcher, MS in Engineering Psychology, BS in Applied Psychology; <strong>Bob Evans</strong>, tool maker dedicated to augmenting human intelligence and quality of life by providing tools to support analysis and exploration of daily experience. </div>\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"You Can’t Be Serious?! – LEGO® Serious Play® - Serious Solution Crafting for Kids aged 3 to 103.\"]We all loved tinkering when were kids… but have you ever considered using colourful bricks as a serious business tool? Placing the experience at the heart of matters, we’re inviting participants to flex their haptic muscles; building metaphors, &amp; conjuring meaning through tactile story making. This invigorating, hands-on solution crafting won’t disappoint. So, don’t be surprised if you LEGO® of your inhibitions…[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Dörte Töllner</strong> and <strong>Cori Moore</strong> of Point-Blank International, Marketing Research &amp; Consultancy, Berlin, Germany </div>\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"Studying In and Out: Linking Organizational and Consumer Ethnography; Suggested Time: 3 Hours\"]Consumer ethnographers are quite capable of describing and explaining the relationships among products, services, consumers, and customers when called upon to do so by a business client. But when we do not understand the organization’s culture, “silos,” internal power relationships, view of staff, and stakeholder dynamics, our understandings may not translate into meaningful responses. Come to this workshop to learn strategies for maximizing your impact with organizational leaders, while doing the work of understanding products, services, consumers, and customers!\r\n\r\nWe are two business anthropologists: one of us specializes in organizational-culture and change, and the other in global products, services, and markets. We introduce case material from a variety of industries in which organizations struggled to respond to emerging consumer preferences and expectations. When a shopper cannot find the product she is looking for, when a patient is poorly treated at a hospital, or when an employee finds that he cannot perform well in his chaotic work environment, we can link an understanding of those shoppers, patients, or employees with corporate practices. Thus, our task becomes one of examining the relationship among organizations and end-users, and not simply the relationships among end-users and products or services. In fact, what we find may scare the bejezus out of our clients (or ourselves), but we will discuss that!\r\n\r\nSo, bring your knowledge of consumers, research, and consulting to bear on the cases we present. After we tell our ethnographic tales, we will invite you to talk about how you have widened the ethnographic lens to incorporate studying “out” and “in” – that is, studying both the culture(s) of consumption and your clients’ culture(s), and the connections between them. Deliverables for the workshop include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Some theoretical approaches and practical techniques linking consumer/customer/product/service findings to organizational barriers and enablers</li>\r\n	<li>Strategies for communicating broader-focused results to organizational leaders</li>\r\n	<li>Key principles to help organizations overcome internal resistance and inertia in the face of research results that challenge organizational practices and ideologies</li>\r\n	<li>Circumstances under which ethnographic research is likely to encourage beneficial organizational or societal adaptation or change.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by: <strong>Elizabeth Briody</strong>, Founder and Principal, Cultural Keys LLC; <strong>Ken Erickson</strong>, Clinical Assistant Professor, Moore College of Business, University of South Carolina, and CEO of Pacific Ethnography Company</div>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<strong>More sessions to come! </strong><em>','Workshops','','inherit','open','open','','605-revision-v1','','','2014-05-27 18:45:53','2014-05-27 18:45:53','',605,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/605-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(634,1,'2014-05-27 19:02:06','2014-05-27 19:02:06','<h4><strong>Sunday, September 7, 2014</h4>\r\n<h5><strong>Morning Session:</strong> 9:30-12:30</h5>\r\n[expand title=\"Consumer Social Responsibility\"]This seminar-format workshop is aimed at exploring the consumer\'s role in shaping the social environment and focuses on demand-side issues of social responsibility. Participants of the workshop will draw on and share their own consumer behavior (a paragraph prepared prior to the workshop) to explore issues such as the trade-off between individual consumer value and societal value, consumer response to corporate social (ir)responsibility, and avenues to promote more socially responsible consumption. Participants will use their material to discuss balancing socially responsible consumption and employ a follow up tool – V-Positive – to provide input for specific brands and consumer responses.[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Luke Kachersky</strong>, Assistant Professor of Marketing, Fordham</div>\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"Explorations: Creativity and Magic at Work\"]Po