ned Google in 2008 and leads an interdisciplinary laboratory\r\ncombining neuroscience, machine learning, advanced hardware design, and biometrics\r\nto pursue projects advancing both basic science and research methods and\r\ntechnologies. Prior to ATAP, he authored many research projects including Project\r\nOxygen—an influential study quantifying the impact of effective people\r\nmanagement—featured in The New York Times, Harvard Business Review, and named\r\none of HR Executive Magazines Most Innovative HR ideas in 2011. He is concurrently\r\nfinishing a PhD in Computational Sociology at the University of Chicago.\r\n\r\n<strong>Discussant:</strong> <em>Christian Madsbjerg, ReD Associates</em>\r\nChristian is a Senior Partner at ReD Associates. He has been leading projects and client\r\nprograms since ReD’s foundation. He holds a specialist role in ReD as director of client\r\nrelations and focuses on ways to rigorously study human behavior and on ways to\r\nunderstand why particular methodologies need to be applied in order to do so. He\r\nwrites, teaches, and speaks about the kinds of methods and reasoning needed for\r\nfact-based investigations of human activity, emotions, and decision-making processes.\r\nHe is the author of books on social theory, discourse analysis, and politics. Christian\r\nstudied philosophy and political science in Copenhagen and London; and has a Masters\r\nfrom the University of London. He is one of EPIC’s Keynote Speakers for 2014.','Salons','','inherit','open','open','','673-revision-v1','','','2014-07-03 14:10:24','2014-07-03 14:10:24','',673,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/673-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(675,1,'2014-07-03 14:11:00','2014-07-03 14:11:00','(New at EPIC 2014)\r\n\r\nAt EPIC, we continually strive to provide relevance for our community, keep us connected through ideas and approaches from each other’s work, and inform attendees of the latest in praxis, thought leadership and innovative approaches to our work, in and out of industry. This year we introduce an exciting happening, long requested by EPIC attendees: a book exhibit that will allow members of the community to introduce their recently published books.\r\n\r\nWe have had requests for a book exhibit for many years, from authors as well as publishing companies and book sellers. All of us want to know the most exciting, most significant books of the season that have a direct connection to our work. And so this year we have decided to initiate our very first Authors’ Space. In order to provide some structure, we’ve asked that books be topically relevant and recent (published in 2010 or later) but also that authors have a significant link to the EPIC community, be that through administrative or community work or papers, workshops, Pecha Kucha’s and the like. We ended up with a list of 10 committed authors who are looking forward to meeting with their fans and responding to the questions of would-be writers.\r\n\r\nDuring Monday and Tuesday, sets of authors and readers will have “place and space” (a table and a two-hour time slot to be exact) to get to know each other and the books everybody has been hearing about. There will be fliers and stacks of books to touch, peruse, get signed and even buy in the middle of the hustle and bustle of EPIC activities. (EPIC, the organization, will not be involved in financial transactions.) A pin-up board will give the times specific authors will be “in residence” at which table at the Authors’ Space.\r\n\r\nThe Authors’ Space will be set up in the Lobby of Pope Auditorium, the main activity center for EPIC. Do mark your calendar to step away from the main events for a few minutes on Monday or Tuesday, to join EPIC authors and their fans in conversation and collegiality.\r\n\r\nThis will also be an opportunity for aspiring EPIC writers to talk with “published authors” about the craft of writing with its practical and emotional joys and hurdles. We have given each author a 2-hour time slot and a table to provide a space for unencumbered shoptalk – the burning logistical questions of “how do I organize my materials” or “how do I get a publisher”, as well as the emotional personal ones like “what do I do when my writing affects my work and family” or “how do I deal with writer’s block.” You may wonder if you should write from an outline or is it better to “just go with the flow”? How do these authors fit writing into their already full life? What if you think you have a dynamite idea but no time to write?\r\n\r\nPlease note that the 2014 Authors’ Space is experimental and is devoted to increasing community resources and commitment this year. Looking ahead to a possible expansion, we’d like to ask you to send us your thoughts. This year, we are looking at what books have been published in the last 4 years by EPIC members. Should that scope be expanded? For example, should an older publication date be allowed for books with essential relevance for the EPIC community? We also have required that authors be personally present in order to underline the importance of face-to-face communication of ideas in our business. But should we also invite selected publishers who have been printing the works of our authors? What are the most important needs of new and aspiring writers within out community? What can EPIC do to support those needs? Please send your ideas to gitti.jordan@gmail.com.\r\n\r\nIt will be an exciting series of days. We are looking forward to seeing you at the Authors’ Space at EPIC2014.\r\n\r\nBrigitte Jordan\r\n\r\nCurator, Authors’ Space\r\n(with Ken Anderson, Timothy Malefyt and Linda Purcell)','The Authors’ Space ','','publish','closed','closed','','the-authors-space','','','2014-07-03 14:12:49','2014-07-03 14:12:49','',0,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/?page_id=675',0,'page','',0),(676,1,'2014-07-03 14:11:00','2014-07-03 14:11:00','(New at EPIC 2014)\r\n\r\nAt EPIC, we continually strive to provide relevance for our community, keep us connected through ideas and approaches from each other’s work, and inform attendees of the latest in praxis, thought leadership and innovative approaches to our work, in and out of industry. This year we introduce an exciting happening, long requested by EPIC attendees: a book exhibit that will allow members of the community to introduce their recently published books.\r\n\r\nWe have had requests for a book exhibit for many years, from authors as well as publishing companies and book sellers. All of us want to know the most exciting, most significant books of the season that have a direct connection to our work. And so this year we have decided to initiate our very first Authors’ Space. In order to provide some structure, we’ve asked that books be topically relevant and recent (published in 2010 or later) but also that authors have a significant link to the EPIC community, be that through administrative or community work or papers, workshops, Pecha Kucha’s and the like. We ended up with a list of 10 committed authors who are looking forward to meeting with their fans and responding to the questions of would-be writers.\r\n\r\nDuring Monday and Tuesday, sets of authors and readers will have “place and space” (a table and a two-hour time slot to be exact) to get to know each other and the books everybody has been hearing about. There will be fliers and stacks of books to touch, peruse, get signed and even buy in the middle of the hustle and bustle of EPIC activities. (EPIC, the organization, will not be involved in financial transactions.) A pin-up board will give the times specific authors will be “in residence” at which table at the Authors’ Space.\r\n\r\nThe Authors’ Space will be set up in the Lobby of Pope Auditorium, the main activity center for EPIC. Do mark your calendar to step away from the main events for a few minutes on Monday or Tuesday, to join EPIC authors and their fans in conversation and collegiality.\r\n\r\nThis will also be an opportunity for aspiring EPIC writers to talk with “published authors” about the craft of writing with its practical and emotional joys and hurdles. We have given each author a 2-hour time slot and a table to provide a space for unencumbered shoptalk – the burning logistical questions of “how do I organize my materials” or “how do I get a publisher”, as well as the emotional personal ones like “what do I do when my writing affects my work and family” or “how do I deal with writer’s block.” You may wonder if you should write from an outline or is it better to “just go with the flow”? How do these authors fit writing into their already full life? What if you think you have a dynamite idea but no time to write?\r\n\r\nPlease note that the 2014 Authors’ Space is experimental and is devoted to increasing community resources and commitment this year. Looking ahead to a possible expansion, we’d like to ask you to send us your thoughts. This year, we are looking at what books have been published in the last 4 years by EPIC members. Should that scope be expanded? For example, should an older publication date be allowed for books with essential relevance for the EPIC community? We also have required that authors be personally present in order to underline the importance of face-to-face communication of ideas in our business. But should we also invite selected publishers who have been printing the works of our authors? What are the most important needs of new and aspiring writers within out community? What can EPIC do to support those needs? Please send your ideas to gitti.jordan@gmail.com.\r\n\r\nIt will be an exciting series of days. We are looking forward to seeing you at the Authors’ Space at EPIC2014.\r\n\r\nBrigitte Jordan\r\n\r\nCurator, Authors’ Space\r\n(with Ken Anderson, Timothy Malefyt and Linda Purcell)','The Authors’ Space ','','inherit','open','open','','675-revision-v1','','','2014-07-03 14:11:00','2014-07-03 14:11:00','',675,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/675-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(677,1,'2014-07-03 14:12:10','2014-07-03 14:12:10','<h3>Top 3 Confirmed Submissions</h3>\r\n<h4>Stokes Jones, Salons Committee</h4>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Assessing CSR Salon:</strong>\r\n<strong><em>Corporate Social Responsibility &amp; Ethnographic Indicators</em></strong>\r\n\r\nIn this Salon attendees will consider questions about the nature and extent to which\r\nethnographic research can (or should) help businesses become tools for social change.\r\nFor example, this group will discuss how (and if) ethnographic research can enable\r\nfirms to better:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Create a material positive impact on society and the environment;</li>\r\n	<li>Expand their fiduciary duty (beyond mere financial profitability) when making decisions;</li>\r\n	<li> Report their overall social and environmental performance (using recognized third-party standards)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBusiness interests claim corporate social responsibility programs (CSR) are ‘the right\r\nthing to do,’ AND that acting responsibly is ‘good for business.’ Yet critics often argue\r\nCSR is mainly PR by other means, or a way to soothe corporate consciences for the\r\ninequality or questionable practices they maintain. This Salon will challenge\r\nparticipants to move CSR past lip service to its ideals by proposing and exploring ‘key\r\nperformance indicators’ that ethnographic research could be a prime source for. This\r\nSalon group will likewise consider the extent to which there is already ethnographic\r\nevidence linked to fulfilling the areas above. We will investigate audit roles for\r\napplied ethnographers; as well as process improvement opportunities for guiding\r\ncompanies to become more socially responsible and resource-efficient.\r\n\r\n<strong>Host:</strong> <em>Stokes Jones, Motorola/Lenovo</em>\r\nStokes trained as a social anthropologist at the London School of Economics; conducting\r\nfieldwork on new reproductive technology in Britain, and emerging consumers in\r\nChina’s Shenzhen Economic Zone. He is Principal Researcher at Motorola focusing on\r\nthe globalization of mobility.\r\n\r\n<strong>Discussant:</strong> <em>Ed Liebow, American Anthropological Association</em>\r\nBefore joining the AAA as Executive Director, Ed had a long and versatile career in\r\nsocial, environmental, and public health policy research. He earned a PhD in cultural\r\nanthropology from Arizona State University.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Accounting For Our Value Salon:</strong>\r\n<strong><em>Crafting Ethnography’s Rhetorics of Justification</em></strong>\r\n<blockquote><em>“Another competing condition…requires that ethnographic research not be\r\nabsorbed into the pure instrumentality of shortterm\r\ncost benefit relations\r\nsubordinated to current management practices lest it loses its distinctive ability to\r\ncontribute fresh perspectives and thereby earn its keep”<em>\r\nMichael Fischer (2009:229)</em></em></blockquote>\r\nAll professions have to work at how they account for their value. It is no different for\r\nmembers of the EPIC community. Ten+ years ago value was talked about in terms of\r\ndiscovery – bringing something to business conversation that wasn’t there previously.\r\nAlong the way, we’ve argued for the value of ethnography as a means of creating\r\nintimacy or empathy. More recently arguments for the value of our work entail\r\ntangible solutions to challenges in the form of products, services or strategies.\r\nFamiliarity with our work has evolved and expectations have shifted. Equally, the\r\nchanging business environment in which we operate leads to comparison with different\r\nor and competing approaches, paradigms or philosophies (e.g., Big Data, Lean or ‘Fail\r\nFast’).\r\n\r\nAny accounting of value is enmeshed in/constrained by larger discourses of business.\r\nSelling ethnographic analysis entails engagement with prevailing rhetorics. While, as a\r\ncommunity of practitioners we straddle different contexts and make different\r\narguments, there remains a fundamental question: How do we mediate prevailing\r\ndiscourses in a way that retains fidelity of voice and ensures a future?\r\n\r\nThe work of accounting for and defending our value and presence will always be a\r\nsignificant feature of our community and its practice; the means by which we do so,\r\nhowever, performs the future. In this Salon we want participants to explore how best\r\nto market, communicate, and represent ourselves and our value as ethnographers in\r\nthe business world (beyond the scope of each project):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>How did we represent our value in the past (when practices were newer/conditions different)?</li>\r\n	<li>What are the prevailing discourses to master currently? How do we insert ourselves into the rhetorics of corporate success today?</li>\r\n	<li>How might we respond to changes in business and corporate environments to re-cast or reformulate our accountings of value?</li>\r\n	<li>At what point do we challenge corporate practices we are asked to engage with that we believe do NOT add value?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBring your past, present, and wished-for ‘accountings of value’ with you!\r\n\r\n<strong>Host:</strong> <em>Simon Roberts, Stripe Partners</em>\r\nSimon established Stripe Partners in late 2013 but has been applying anthropology to\r\ncommercial and policy contexts since 2001 – first with Ideas Bazaar, the UK’s first\r\nethnographic research consultancy, then at Intel where he set up Intel’s first social science-led\r\nlab in Europe. More recently he was at ReD Associates. Simon has a PhD in Anthropology\r\nfrom The University of Edinburgh.\r\n\r\n<strong>Discussant:</strong> <em>Rita Denny, Practica Group LLC</em>\r\nRita is an anthropologist and a founding partner of Practica Group, a consumer research and\r\nstrategic consultancy based in NYC and Chicago, where she brings sociocultural analysis to\r\nnew product and brand development, retail display, and communication strategies for Fortune\r\n500 companies. With Patricia Sunderland, Rita is author of Doing Anthropology in Consumer\r\nResearch and editor of the Handbook of Anthropology in Business (2014).\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<strong>Debating Ethnographic Epistemology Salon:</strong>\r\n<strong><em>Should Corporate Ethnography Even Attempt To Avoid Reductionism?</em></strong>\r\n\r\nWe are accustomed to thinking about ethnography as a fundamentally descriptive,\r\nobservational methodology. This is because culture and society is a complex web of\r\nrelationships, gestures, symbols, and unarticulated practices operating in a non-linear\r\nfashion. Individuals both adapt to cultural frameworks, and are themselves agents\r\nengaged in the social reproduction of the systems that support them. Yet we live in a\r\npost-structural era, where the attempt to distill universal conclusions about subjects\r\noften conveys anthropologists to problematic territory. Today few academics even\r\naspire to a comprehensive depiction of social ‘structure’ or ‘function’ as founded by\r\nMalinowski, Evans-Pritchard, or Levi-Strauss, for it risks the Geertzian critique of\r\noversimplification and reductionism. Hence Professors speak in terms of\r\n“negotiations,” or “tendencies,” capturing complexity in nuanced, ambivalent\r\ndescriptions.\r\n\r\nThis puts ethnographers who practice in the context of industry in a precarious place.\r\nFirms have little use for purely academic ‘stories’ about people—they expect to learn\r\nhow to sell more (or design right) for their consumers. These ethnographers,\r\ntherefore, are compelled to represent findings in visual models that reduce\r\ncomplexity to uni-directional relationships that steer clients toward specific courses\r\nof action. Whereas the research may be rigorous—the client consumes an often\r\nsimplistic “deliverable” embodying causal assumptions. Or they present pithy\r\n“consumer insights” which convey observations with the implicit understanding that\r\nclients are seeking causal linkages. Clients respond to “actionable” research by\r\nassuming “consumers value [x], therefore if I integrate [x] into my product, then I will\r\npositively influence y.” Taken together, this process implicates practicing\r\nethnographers in the transmission of causal assumptions, implicitly embodied in their\r\ndeliverables in a variety of ways. These conclusions, potentially, obscure the\r\nnon-linear complexity of human systems. Or, do they, at a meta level, accurately reflect\r\nthe looping effect of ‘power’ on any discourse aiming at ‘knowledge’.\r\n\r\nThis Salon will offer a lively forum for discussion about how ethnographers convey\r\n‘truth’ to clients, and open up for debate the role of causal inference in ethnography,\r\nasking if it is time to embrace the benefits of reductionism, and thereby expand the\r\ndefinition of our discipline beyond that of a “descriptive science”?\r\n\r\n<strong>Host:</strong> <em>Neal H. Patel, Google</em>\r\nNeal works in the Google Advanced Technology and Projects, Human &amp; Social Dynamics\r\nLaboratory. Neal joined Google in 2008 and leads an interdisciplinary laboratory\r\ncombining neuroscience, machine learning, advanced hardware design, and biometrics\r\nto pursue projects advancing both basic science and research methods and\r\ntechnologies. Prior to ATAP, he authored many research projects including Project\r\nOxygen—an influential study quantifying the impact of effective people\r\nmanagement—featured in The New York Times, Harvard Business Review, and named\r\none of HR Executive Magazines Most Innovative HR ideas in 2011. He is concurrently\r\nfinishing a PhD in Computational Sociology at the University of Chicago.\r\n\r\n<strong>Discussant:</strong> <em>Christian Madsbjerg, ReD Associates</em>\r\nChristian is a Senior Partner at ReD Associates. He has been leading projects and client\r\nprograms since ReD’s foundation. He holds a specialist role in ReD as director of client\r\nrelations and focuses on ways to rigorously study human behavior and on ways to\r\nunderstand why particular methodologies need to be applied in order to do so. He\r\nwrites, teaches, and speaks about the kinds of methods and reasoning needed for\r\nfact-based investigations of human activity, emotions, and decision-making processes.\r\nHe is the author of books on social theory, discourse analysis, and politics. Christian\r\nstudied philosophy and political science in Copenhagen and London; and has a Masters\r\nfrom the University of London. He is one of EPIC’s Keynote Speakers for 2014.','Salons','','inherit','open','open','','673-revision-v1','','','2014-07-03 14:12:10','2014-07-03 14:12:10','',673,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/673-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(678,1,'2014-07-03 16:30:16','2014-07-03 16:30:16','','Schedule','','inherit','open','open','','537-revision-v1','','','2014-07-03 16:30:16','2014-07-03 16:30:16','',537,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/537-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(679,1,'2014-07-03 16:35:56','2014-07-03 16:35:56','','Schedule','','inherit','open','open','','537-revision-v1','','','2014-07-03 16:35:56','2014-07-03 16:35:56','',537,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/537-revision-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(680,1,'2014-07-08 16:15:28','2014-07-08 16:15:28','<h4><strong>Sunday, September 7, 2014</strong></h4>\r\n<h5><strong>Morning Session:</strong> 9:30-12:30</h5>\r\n[expand title=\"Consumer Social Responsibility\"]<img data-id=\"484\"  src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/Claro.jpg\" alt=\"Claro\" width=\"230\" height=\"200\" class=\"alignleft size-full wp-image-484\" /><br>This seminar-format workshop is aimed at exploring the consumer\'s role in shaping the social environment and focuses on demand-side issues of social responsibility. Participants of the workshop will draw on and share their own consumer behavior (a paragraph prepared prior to the workshop) to explore issues such as the trade-off between individual consumer value and societal value, consumer response to corporate social (ir)responsibility, and avenues to promote more socially responsible consumption. Participants will use their material to discuss balancing socially responsible consumption and employ a follow up tool – V-Positive – to provide input for specific brands and consumer responses.[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Luke Kachersky</strong>, Research Director, Center for Positive Marketing, Assistant Professor of Marketing, Fordham University Schools of Business</div>\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"Explorations: Creativity and Magic at Work\"]Politicians, corporate executives, civil servants, and academics talk about “creative industries,” “creative hubs” (or clusters), “creative cities,” “creative classes,” assigning high cultural prestige to what were previously mundane business activities. Yet, the words “creative” and “creativity” are pushed aside and treated as existing in a well-cushioned vacuum. All that is required to nourish creativity, it seems, are the right kinds of people gathered in the right kinds of spaces doing the right kinds of creative activity. In this sense, most people in business, education, and political administration appear to believe in creativity as a form of “magic”.\r\n\r\nThis workshop seeks to answer the question: “what is creativity?” To do this, it looks at a number of different case studies of creativity at work (a ceramic art exhibition, an advertising campaign, editing a woman’s fashion magazine). Is creativity no more than cultural bricolage, based on the past experiences of those involved? Or is it possible for those working in business situations to come up with genuinely creative innovations? If so, what facilitates and what hinders them? And what are the different values and types of evaluation (technical, social, aesthetic, financial, and so on) brought to bear by the different people working together on a project (design, advertising, fashion, film, and so on)? In other words, how is the meaning of creativity negotiated?\r\n\r\nParticipants are invited to bring their own ethnographic experiences to bear as we explore creativity at work in different business contexts. In particular, they will be asked to reflect on their ethnographic practices and experiences. How, as consultants, can they contribute to a client’s creative environment?\r\n<em><strong>Workshop Outcomes</strong></em> By attending this workshop, participants will gain an understanding of:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>What creativity is and how it works in practice in different business situations;</li>\r\n	<li>The different kinds of values that different people involved bring to bear on the creative process as they negotiate their individual meanings of “creativity”;</li>\r\n	<li>How best to apply these insights to their own research practices.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by<strong> Brian Moeran</strong>, Editor, <em>Journal of Business Anthropology</em>, Professor, Copenhagen Business School/University of Hong Kong</div>\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"Toward Conceptual, Methodological, and Ethical Standards of Practice in Business Anthropology\"]The rapid growth of business anthropology over the last decades and the adoption of ethnography by numerous professionals in a variety of industries, some trained, some not, suggests the importance of defining the character of business anthropology, so that as anthropology is increasingly adopted outside the academic world it continues to maintain distinctive content and high standards of practice. Historically, the structure of authority in anthropology was clear and monolithic with academic institutions defining the field. Today, a majority of anthropologists are pursuing their profession outside the academic world, increasingly in business. Concurrently, many non-anthropologists have engaged in business anthropology, especially ethnography. At this historical juncture it would be beneficial to have a statement defining the educational, conceptual, and methodological foundations of the field that emanated from qualified business anthropologists. This workshop is an initial step in an ongoing discussion of the character of business anthropology, ultimately leading to some document that expresses standards for the field.\r\n\r\nStandards in themselves can be either aspirational or demarcational: they can either present something for the larger community to aspire to, or they can be used to draw boundaries distinguishing legitimate practitioners from others. Mature professions, such as law, medicine, architecture, and engineering, have established their professional identities, combining academic preparation, board certification, and state licensure: these are typically the result of numerous years of discussion and negotiation. For the present, within anthropology, it is important not to draw boundaries between what is and is not business anthropology, but rather to hold up models of excellence that practitioners might aspire to, and to create a shared understanding of educational, methodological, and ethical foundations.\r\n\r\nThe workshop will have four objectives or questions to be answered:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Should there be ongoing discussion and perhaps codification of the educational, methodological, and ethical foundations or standards of business anthropology?</li>\r\n	<li>If so, what is the substantive content such an intiative, and how broadly should foundations and/or standards be defined?</li>\r\n	<li>How, where and when should foundations and/or standards be presented? Do they need to be adopted by a professional society? Which one?</li>\r\n	<li>What is the best means for building a network for propagating these practices?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWorkshop participants will be given required readings that will inform their discussion. The exact content of the workshop will combine general discussion, ideation, and possibly two or three breakout groups to work on specific issues. It will conclude with crafting a draft statement of principles. [/expand]\r\n\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Allen Batteau</strong>, Associate Professor, Wayne State University, and <strong>Robert Morais</strong>, Principle, Weinman, Schnee, Morais, Inc.</div>\r\n<h5><strong>Afternoon Session:</strong> 1:30-4:30</h5>\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"You too can collect “big data”! How to combine quant and qual data to create a holistic picture of your users.\"]\r\nThere is much interest in the topic of Big Data. However, many researchers are unclear how to combine rich or “thick,” ethnographic data with large-scale quantitative data. This workshop offers an approach, which does not require a computer science degree: ESM via PACO. Experiential Sampling Methodology (ESM) is a type of longitudinal diary study that allows one to understand a person’s experience in the moment. Using a free, open-source mobile app called “PACO (Personal Analytics Companion),” we can conduct large-scale ESM studies with users anywhere in the world. These studies can be conducted after ethnographic studies to ascertain how broadly your observations apply to your user population or they can be done in advance to identify insights you want to study in-person, in-depth.  By combining these methodologies, you create a more holistic understanding of your users.\r\n\r\nIn this three-hour workshop, we will introduce attendees to ESM, discuss ways we have used this methodology at Google, help attendees create their own ESM study, and discuss data analysis. The goal is for every attendee to leave the session equipped with the knowledge to design and create their own ESM study, analyze the data, and make actionable recommendations.  Attendance will be capped at 25 attendees to ensure 1:1 attention and good group discussions.\r\n[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Anna Avrekh</strong>, User Experience Researcher, <strong>Kathy Baxter</strong>, Staff User Experience Researcher, and <strong>Bob Evans</strong>, Software Engineer, Google, Inc. </div>\r\n\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"You Can’t Be Serious?! – LEGO® Serious Play® - Serious Solution Crafting for Kids aged 3 to 103.\"]We all loved tinkering when were kids… but have you ever considered using colourful bricks as a serious business tool? Placing the experience at the heart of matters, we’re inviting participants to flex their haptic muscles; building metaphors, &amp; conjuring meaning through tactile story making. This invigorating, hands-on solution crafting won’t disappoint. So, don’t be surprised if you LEGO® of your inhibitions…[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Dörte Töllner</strong>, Founder and Managing Director and <strong>Cori Moore</strong>, Communications Strategist, Point-Blank International Marketing Research & Consultancy</div>\r\n\r\n[expand title=\"Studying In and Out: Linking Organizational and Consumer Ethnography\"]Consumer ethnographers are quite capable of describing and explaining the relationships among products, services, consumers, and customers when called upon to do so by a business client. But when we do not understand the organization’s culture, “silos,” internal power relationships, view of staff, and stakeholder dynamics, our understandings may not translate into meaningful responses. Come to this workshop to learn strategies for maximizing your impact with organizational leaders, while doing the work of understanding products, services, consumers, and customers!\r\n\r\nWe are two business anthropologists: one of us specializes in organizational-culture and change, and the other in global products, services, and markets. We introduce case material from a variety of industries in which organizations struggled to respond to emerging consumer preferences and expectations. When a shopper cannot find the product she is looking for, when a patient is poorly treated at a hospital, or when an employee finds that he cannot perform well in his chaotic work environment, we can link an understanding of those shoppers, patients, or employees with corporate practices. Thus, our task becomes one of examining the relationship among organizations and end-users, and not simply the relationships among end-users and products or services. In fact, what we find may scare the bejezus out of our clients (or ourselves), but we will discuss that!\r\n\r\nSo, bring your knowledge of consumers, research, and consulting to bear on the cases we present. After we tell our ethnographic tales, we will invite you to talk about how you have widened the ethnographic lens to incorporate studying “out” and “in” – that is, studying both the culture(s) of consumption and your clients’ culture(s), and the connections between them. Deliverables for the workshop include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Some theoretical approaches and practical techniques linking consumer/customer/product/service findings to organizational barriers and enablers</li>\r\n	<li>Strategies for communicating broader-focused results to organizational leaders</li>\r\n	<li>Key principles to help organizations overcome internal resistance and inertia in the face of research results that challenge organizational practices and ideologies</li>\r\n	<li>Circumstances under which ethnographic research is likely to encourage beneficial organizational or societal adaptation or change.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n[/expand]\r\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Elizabeth Briody</strong>, Founder and Principal, Cultural Keys LLC and <strong>Ken Erickson</strong>, Clinical Assistant Professor, Moore College of Business, University of South Carolina, CEO, Pacific Ethnography Company</div>\r\n<strong>More sessions to come! </strong><em></em>','Workshops','','inherit','open','open','','605-autosave-v1','','','2014-07-08 16:15:28','2014-07-08 16:15:28','',605,'http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/605-autosave-v1/',0,'revision','',0),(681,1,'2014-07-09 15:04:11','2014-07-09 15:04:11','<h5>8:30 to 9:00</h5>\n<h4>Breakfast</h4>\n<hr>\n<h5>9:00 to 9:15</h5>\n<h4>Welcome</h4>\n<hr>\n<h5>9:15 to 9:30</h5>\n<h4>Center Index</h4>\n<hr>\n<h5>8:30-9:00</h5>\n<h4>Morning Session</h4>\n[expand title=\"<strong>Workshop:</strong> Consumer Social Responsibility\"]This seminar-format workshop is aimed at exploring the consumer\'s role in shaping the social environment and focuses on demand-side issues of social responsibility. Participants of the workshop will draw on and share their own consumer behavior (a paragraph prepared prior to the workshop) to explore issues such as the trade-off between individual consumer value and societal value, consumer response to corporate social (ir)responsibility, and avenues to promote more socially responsible consumption. Participants will use their material to discuss balancing socially responsible consumption and employ a follow up tool – V-Positive – to provide input for specific brands and consumer responses.[/expand]\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Luke Kachersky</strong>, Assistant Professor of Marketing, Fordham. <a href=\"http://epiconference.com/2014/register/\">Register</a></div>\n[expand title=\"<strong>Workshop:</strong> Explorations: Creativity and Magic at Work\"]Politicians, corporate executives, civil servants, and academics talk about “creative industries,” “creative hubs” (or clusters), “creative cities,” “creative classes,” assigning high cultural prestige to what were previously mundane business activities. Yet, the words “creative” and “creativity” are pushed aside and treated as existing in a well-cushioned vacuum. All that is required to nourish creativity, it seems, are the right kinds of people gathered in the right kinds of spaces doing the right kinds of creative activity. In this sense, most people in business, education, and political administration appear to believe in creativity as a form of “magic”.\n\nThis workshop seeks to answer the question: “what is creativity?” To do this, it looks at a number of different case studies of creativity at work (a ceramic art exhibition, an advertising campaign, editing a woman’s fashion magazine). Is creativity no more than cultural bricolage, based on the past experiences of those involved? Or is it possible for those working in business situations to come up with genuinely creative innovations? If so, what facilitates and what hinders them? And what are the different values and types of evaluation (technical, social, aesthetic, financial, and so on) brought to bear by the different people working together on a project (design, advertising, fashion, film, and so on)? In other words, how is the meaning of creativity negotiated?\n\nParticipants are invited to bring their own ethnographic experiences to bear as we explore creativity at work in different business contexts. In particular, they will be asked to reflect on their ethnographic practices and experiences. How, as consultants, can they contribute to a client’s creative environment?\n<em><strong>Workshop Outcomes</strong></em> By attending this workshop, participants will gain an understanding of:\n<ul>\n	<li>What creativity is and how it works in practice in different business situations;</li>\n	<li>The different kinds of values that different people involved bring to bear on the creative process as they negotiate their individual meanings of “creativity”;</li>\n	<li>How best to apply these insights to their own research practices.</li>\n</ul>\n[/expand]\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Brian Moeran</strong>, Editor, <em>Journal of Business Anthropology</em>, Copenhagen Business School/Univeristy of Hong Kong. <a href=\"http://epiconference.com/2014/register/\">Register</a></div>\n\n\n[expand title=\"<strong>Workshop:</strong> Toward Conceptual, Methodological, and Ethical Standards of Practice in Business Anthropology\"]The rapid growth of business anthropology over the last decades and the adoption of ethnography by numerous professionals in a variety of industries, some trained, some not, suggests the importance of defining the character of business anthropology, so that as anthropology is increasingly adopted outside the academic world it continues to maintain distinctive content and high standards of practice. Historically, the structure of authority in anthropology was clear and monolithic with academic institutions defining the field. Today, a majority of anthropologists are pursuing their profession outside the academic world, increasingly in business. Concurrently, many non-anthropologists have engaged in business anthropology, especially ethnography. At this historical juncture it would be beneficial to have a statement defining the educational, conceptual, and methodological foundations of the field that emanated from qualified business anthropologists. This workshop is an initial step in an ongoing discussion of the character of business anthropology, ultimately leading to some document that expresses standards for the field.\n\nStandards in themselves can be either aspirational or demarcational: they can either present something for the larger community to aspire to, or they can be used to draw boundaries distinguishing legitimate practitioners from others. Mature professions, such as law, medicine, architecture, and engineering, have established their professional identities, combining academic preparation, board certification, and state licensure: these are typically the result of numerous years of discussion and negotiation. For the present, within anthropology, it is important not to draw boundaries between what is and is not business anthropology, but rather to hold up models of excellence that practitioners might aspire to, and to create a shared understanding of educational, methodological, and ethical foundations.\n\nThe workshop will have four objectives or questions to be answered:\n<ul>\n	<li>Should there be ongoing discussion and perhaps codification of the educational, methodological, and ethical foundations or standards of business anthropology?</li>\n	<li>If so, what is the substantive content such an intiative, and how broadly should foundations and/or standards be defined?</li>\n	<li>How, where and when should foundations and/or standards be presented? Do they need to be adopted by a professional society? Which one?</li>\n	<li>What is the best means for building a network for propagating these practices?</li>\n</ul>\nWorkshop participants will be given required readings that will inform their discussion. The exact content of the workshop will combine general discussion, ideation, and possibly two or three breakout groups to work on specific issues. It will conclude with crafting a draft statement of principles. [/expand]\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Allen Batteau</strong>, Associate Professor, Wayne St. U. Detroit; <strong>Robert Morais</strong>, Principle of Weinman, Schnee, Morais, Inc. <a href=\"http://epiconference.com/2014/register/\">Register</a></div>\n<img alt=\"rule\" src=\"http://powinteractive.pairserver.com/epic/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/rule.png\" width=\"100%\" height=\"1\" />\n<h5>1:30-4:30</h5>\n<h4>Afternoon Session</h4>\n[expand title=\"<strong>Workshop:</strong> You too can collect “big data”! How to combine quant and qual data to create a holistic picture of your users.\"]\nThere is much interest in the topic of Big Data. However, many researchers are unclear how to combine rich or “thick,” ethnographic data with large-scale quantitative data. This workshop offers an approach, which does not require a computer science degree: ESM via PACO. Experiential Sampling Methodology (ESM) is a type of longitudinal diary study that allows one to understand a person’s experience in the moment. Using a free, open-source mobile app called “PACO (Personal Analytics Companion),” we can conduct large-scale ESM studies with users anywhere in the world. These studies can be conducted after ethnographic studies to ascertain how broadly your observations apply to your user population or they can be done in advance to identify insights you want to study in-person, in-depth.  By combining these methodologies, you create a more holistic understanding of your users.\n\nIn this three-hour workshop, we will introduce attendees to ESM, discuss ways we have used this methodology at Google, help attendees create their own ESM study, and discuss data analysis. The goal is for every attendee to leave the session equipped with the knowledge to design and create their own ESM study, analyze the data, and make actionable recommendations.  Attendance will be capped at 25 attendees to ensure 1:1 attention and good group discussions.\n[/expand]\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Anna Avrekh</strong>, User Experience Researcher at Google for 9+ years;<strong> Kathy Baxter</strong>, Google Staff User Experience Researcher, MS in Engineering Psychology, BS in Applied Psychology; <strong>Bob Evans</strong>, tool maker dedicated to augmenting human intelligence and quality of life by providing tools to support analysis and exploration of daily experience. <a href=\"http://epiconference.com/2014/register/\">Register</a></div>\n\n[expand title=\"<strong>Workshop:</strong> You Can’t Be Serious?! – LEGO® Serious Play® - Serious Solution Crafting for Kids aged 3 to 103.\"]We all loved tinkering when were kids… but have you ever considered using colourful bricks as a serious business tool? Placing the experience at the heart of matters, we’re inviting participants to flex their haptic muscles; building metaphors, &amp; conjuring meaning through tactile story making. This invigorating, hands-on solution crafting won’t disappoint. So, don’t be surprised if you LEGO® of your inhibitions…[/expand]\n<div class=\"grey-text\">Hosted by <strong>Dörte Töllner</strong> and <strong>Cori Moore</strong> of Point-Blank In